[4] Sierra Leone: with schools closed, forced marriages on the rise
Date: Fri 21 Nov 2014
Source: Plan International [edited]
http://plan-international.org/about-plan/resources/blogs/forced-marriages-on-the-rise-in-the-time-of-ebola


Forced marriages on the rise in the time of Ebola
-------------------------------------------------
My name is Christiana. I am 17 years old. I live in a small village in the Moyamba District in southern Sierra Leone. I lost my father when I was a baby and my mother is a petty trader. I have experienced issues affecting girls' rights to education because I was forced into marriage. I want to be a voice to tackle forced marriage in Sierra Leone and the world....

In my school, Plan Sierra Leone established a girls' club under the Girl Power Project. I was selected by my peers to be their president because of my goal to be an advocate for girls' education and against early marriage, teenage pregnancy and female genital mutilation.

Before the Ebola outbreak, we were having meetings as a group, doing peer education and visiting homes to promote girls' education and discourage early marriage which was prevalent in our community. I have often said: "If you plant a tree and allow it to grow, then expect a fresh fruit from it." Now it is impossible to meet as a group because schools are closed.... -- more

[Byline: Christiana, Plan International youth blogger]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
